      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Introduction</h3>Until now, we have observed how our fingers have helped us create different ways to count. However, this was not always the case. For a long time, we did not have a way to represent the concept of \"all fingers down\". In this text, we will explore a bit of the history of counting and how we arrived at the numbers we use today.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_history",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>The History of our Numbers</h3>The numbers we use today are ancient. We call them Hindu-Arabic numbers because they were initially created in India and, after being introduced to the Arabs, they were expanded and spread around the world (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('7b7d81af-c3ba-43fa-9bd8-06662ee66d1f'); return false;\">Kunitzsch, Paul, <htdate0>, pp. 3 - 21</a>).</p><p>We will primarily use Hindu-Arabic numbers, but we will not forget the Indigenous numbers that we have learned. Given that numbers can have different representations, we have chosen the following to proceed:</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2003",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
