      {
         "id": "SECTION_zero",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Who represented the <b>0</b> first?</h3>We are representing the ten numbers with our hands, but things were not always like this. This knowledge was built over time. The philosopher Socrates, recognizing these constant changes, gave us a significant lesson: <b>\"I know that I know nothing\"</b> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('3b95809f-e017-4f2c-9c30-bc3db69ce7c5'); return false;\">Plato, <htdate0>, pp. 15</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ae49cb80-7652-4fe9-b18a-0de1c4c8321a'); return false;\">Luiz Felipe Pond√©, <htdate1></a>).</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1</b><br />Considering how little we know, what do you think about studying and finding answers to life's questions?</div></div></center></p><p>An example of the advancement of knowledge is the first number in <b>Table 1</b>, the 0, which was one of the last numbers to be represented, despite us having our fingers down for a long time. But who represented the number 0 first? If we begin our answer with, \"The first to represent the 0 was....\", we should keep in mind that our answer may change with new discoveries. Let's look at some examples.</p><p>Auwalu Musa and Anna Blume inform us that although Indigenous peoples created different symbols to represent fingers down, they did not use them in the same way as we do (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3'); return false;\">Musa, Auwalu, <htdate2>, pp. 44</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('9f68915b-60c5-42fc-84ff-3f6e329d09b8'); return false;\">Blume, Anna, <htdate3></a>). Thus, we could conclude that the first to create and use symbols were the Arabs (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3'); return false;\">Musa, Auwalu, <htdate4>, pp. 44</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('7b7d81af-c3ba-43fa-9bd8-06662ee66d1f'); return false;\">Kunitzsch, Paul, <htdate5>, pp. 4</a>). On the other hand, when we study Francisco B. Puente's work, we learn that Indigenous peoples in different parts of the American continent used various methods to represent fingers down (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1'); return false;\">Puente, Francisco Barriga, <htdate6></a>).</p><p>Based on what we have seen, we can affirm that different peoples represented fingers down in different ways.</p>",
